Growing up, I would watch Kelly Ripa on TV when I would stay home sick from school. She, along with many other female broadcasters I watched, is one of the reasons I am doing what I do today. So, to sit down with her for this deeply personal conversation was a career highlight and not an assignment I took lightly. 

In person, Kelly is everything you think and more. What you see on TV is what you get! But in this cover story, Kelly does not sugarcoat the news, as she expertly does with a smile on her show every morning. In this conversation, Kelly opens about about the sexist struggles she privately faced behind the scenes, as she publicly continued to lead “Live!” to record ratings for more than 22 years (!!) In this piece, Kelly explains that she is speaking up in hopes of encouraging other women to recognize their value in the workplace, earn their well-deserved money and fight for themselves.

Thank you @kellyripa! And congrats on being one of @variety’s #PowerOfWomen honorees — the true definition of a powerful woman!

I also loved speaking with her TV hubby @ryanseacrest & her real life hubby @instasuelos, who was shocked she agreed to accept an award! 

Head over to Variety.com or pick up your magazine on newsstands this week to read Kelly’s story.

It took me all day to come up with a caption & I’m still at a loss for words…but…we were nominated for an Emmy!!! 🏆 

“Variety Studio: Actors on Actors” was nominated for a daytime Emmy today!! 

When I started at @variety nearly 9 years ago in 2014, the first season of “Actors on Actors” debuted — and I always loved the series. Shortly after starting in our newsroom, I began working on AoA with a variety (pun intended) of different roles over the years: first, as a researcher helping with questions, then as an off-camera moderator helping facilitate the conversations on-set. And finally a few seasons ago, I was asked by our fierce and fabulous executive producer @sbauntie to host along with @awardscircuit. (We also write the scripts for the show!) That was a dream come true moment to be trusted with a show that I had adored and respected for all these years, and even more meaningful knowing that I worked my way up the ranks over the years.

I am so grateful for the opportunities my hard work and perseverance has afforded me, forever indebted to those who have mentored, supported and believed in me & beyond proud to be part of this team!! Nothing is handed to you…it’s earned. And of course, nothing is earned alone. We did it! What a week!!

Out today: my latest cover for @variety’s special Emmy issues, starring the absolute force that is @niecynash1 💥 

I spoke to Niecy about how her own personal tragedy connected her to the subject matter of #Dahmer — in which she plays the hero and heartbeat of the show, Glenda Cleveland — stealing scenes, even with the phenomenal Evan Peters. Niecy talks about the immense responsibility she felt to tell the story of Glenda, a Black woman whose voice was ignored by authorities. Like so many in her community, Niecy says she has felt unseen and unheard throughout her career. 

“This story is timeless,” she says. “Systematic racism & differential treatment are still alive & well.” 

Niecy also recalls the first time she saw herself represented on-screen when she was watching television with her “grandmama,” and saw Lola Falana. (I love this quote.) “I looked at my grandmother and I said, ‘That’s what I want to be: I want to be Black, fabulous and on TV.’ … And boom! I’m Black. I’m fabulous. And I’m on TV.”

A huge congrats to @emilylongeretta for overseeing all of our #Emmys issues. This is a huge undertaking — from booking talent, assigning, writing, editing — and she’s done it like a boss! I’m a proud friend. ❤️ And congrats to @dandoperalski on capturing extraordinary photographs for this entire portfolio.

Head to @variety to read all the #Emmys issues — rolling out over the next week!

Surprise! Last weekend, Michael and I were married in front of our family in the backyard. We wanted to have an intimate ceremony with our parents, siblings, my two grandmas and our witnesses, before we head off to celebrate with all of our friends and loved ones at our wedding this weekend.

With all of the loss and devastation in the world right now, we feel grateful to have a reason to smile. As the rabbi said before Michael stepped on the glass, “the goodness of your union can fix the broken parts of the world, as symbolized by the broken glass.”

The lace blouse I wore is the same blouse my mom wore 40 years ago when she married my dad in 1983. The rabbi who married us is the same rabbi who bat mitzvah’d me 20 years ago in 2003. The tallit hanging above us was worn by Michael’s dad at his bar mitzvah more than 50 years ago, and the one wrapped around us was a gift to my dad on my parents’ wedding day from my great grandfather, whom I am named after. Our traditional gold bands were custom made by my dear friend @zameerkassam. And our ketubah, which is a Jewish marriage license, was created by an artist @noa_papercuts in Israel. I commissioned her to create this beautiful piece long before the war broke out. It now takes on a greater meaning of a more peaceful time.

We are so excited as we head into our wedding weekend, but at the same time, cannot stop thinking of the constant news coverage surrounding all of the innocent civilians in both Israel and Gaza and the families suffering right now. 🤍🕊️

Well…we really had no idea how meaningful our little backyard ceremony would be.

After 9 years, I have made the tough decision to leave Variety. I am excited to share where I’m headed to next, but first…

Thank you to my colleagues for teaching me every day. You have all become family, and I am so proud of what we’ve accomplished together. I stepped foot into Variety at 24 years old, and was terrified to work alongside legendary writers and editors. A special thanks to Ramin Setoodeh, Cynthia Littleton, Michelle Sobrino, Gerry Byrne and Jay Penske. You all have supported my ambitions, taken chances on my big ideas and allowed me to evolve and grow into the journalist I am today. I can never thank you enough.

Where to begin? I have written 10 covers, published thousands of stories and interviewed Oscar winners, studio chiefs and every Bachelor star in the history of reality TV. I have reported from Sundance, Cannes, the Academy Awards and more premieres than I can count. I’ve had the opportunity to appear across networks and work with the most accomplished producers in the business. I’ve witnessed history from the women’s march, Britney Spears’ conservatorship case and at the courthouse covering the trials of Harvey Weinstein, Danny Masterson and Bill Cosby. I have been at the frontlines of the #MeToo movement and am forever grateful to all of the sources who have trusted me. Seeing the work of journalists change society is not something I ever imagined. My interview with the Kardashians is ingrained in pop culture history. I have been called a dimwit on national TV by Bill O’Reilly. I have co-hosted the red carpet shows that I grew up watching. I have been live on-air after more red eye flights than I’d like to admit, and I’ve moved cross-country 4x during my tenure at Variety. I started as a researcher on Actors on Actors, and worked my way up to hosting the show, landing my first Emmy nomination. I have truly grown up in this newsroom.

I love the creativity and craziness of this industry. To all of you across the biz: I look forward to continuing the work in my next chapter.

To my Variety fam: I will miss you more than you know. But I can’t wait to be your biggest fan. ❤️

One of the best parts about my job over the past decade has been getting the opportunity to appear across networks & meet so many wonderful people. From producers to anchors to stage managers to bookers to hair and makeup, I have made friends on different sets throughout the years & have learned an immense amount about the TV business from so many different incredible talents.
